AVIAN INFLUENZA H5N2, POULTRY - USA (TEXAS) (03): OIE
********************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: 24 Feb 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Office International des Epizooties(OIE), Disease Information [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/Messages/040224USA.htm>

Highly Pathogenic Avian Influenza in the United States of America
-----------------------------------------------
(Date of previous outbreak of highly pathogenic avian influenza in the
United States of America reported to the OIE: 1984).
Information received on 23 Feb 2004 from Dr Peter Fernandez, Associate
Administrator, Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service, United States
Department of Agriculture (USDA), Washington, DC:
Date of the report: 23 Feb 2004.
An outbreak of avian influenza was reported in Gonzalez County, State of
Texas. This detection was made under the routine State monitoring programme
for avian influenza.
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 17 Feb 2004.
Estimated date of primary infection: 15 Feb 2004.
Description of affected population: chickens. The [caretakers of the] flock
did not practice any biosecurity.
Total number of animals in the outbreak: approx. 6600 chickens.
Causal agent: avian influenza virus strain H5N2. [Note by the OIE Animal
Health Information Department: The USDA confirmed that the H5N2 strain of
avian influenza in a flock of chickens in Texas is highly pathogenic avian
influenza].
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: unknown at this time.
B. Other epidemiological details:
- Birds raised on the premises were being sold to supply the live bird
markets in metropolitan areas (Houston).
- Poultry premises within a 16-km radius of the index case are being
sampled and tested. To date, premises tested within this radius are
negative for avian influenza.
Control measures:
- stamping-out;
- quarantine;
- movement control inside the country;
- screening;
- surveillance.
OIE Animal Health Information Department
<information.dept@oie.int>
Further details will be published in the next issue of Weekly Disease
Information, available on line as from Fri 27 Feb 2004 afternoon (GMT).
